column3: An assailant stole a box truck and crashed into a vehicle and a house at the intersection of Shirley street and Cross street in Winthrop, Massachusetts, United States. Following the crash, the assailant attempted to hijack a second vehicle, then walked down Shirley street armed with two pistols. The assailant shot and killed two black civilians before he was shot and killed by police. Two additional civilians were injured in the initial crash. No group claimed responsibility for the incident; however, sources identified the assailant as Nathan Allen. Investigators noted that Allen had kept journals he referred to as "The Allen Diaries" in which he drew swastikas and espoused white supremacist views, including the belief that racism was "healthy and natural." Sources also suspected that Allen may have intended to target nearby Jewish temples prior to the crash.
column12: "Gunman who killed two people after crashing stolen truck is fatally shot by police in Massachusetts," CNN, June 26, 2021.

column3: Between 1:00 and 2:00 PM during a joint session of Congress to certify Electoral College votes, several hundred assailants attacked Capitol Police officers and breached the security perimeter of the United States Capitol complex in Washington, District of Columbia, United States. The assailants then entered the Capitol building and searched for members of Congress, assaulted responding police personnel, ransacked Congressional offices, and destroyed property for approximately four hours until 6:00 P.M. when police personnel were able to clear out the remaining assailants. One person was killed in the assault by police gunfire when she attempted to climb through a window and breach the Speaker's Lobby. At least 114 police officers and at least 68 assailants were injured, and several members of Congress and staff aides were forced to barricade during the incident. This was one of three related incidents near the U.S. Capitol on this date. In a post on the group's website two days before the attack, Oath Keepers leader Stewart Rhodes called for members to travel to Washington, D.C. on January 6 "in support of President TrumpÂ’s fight to defeat the enemies foreign and domestic who are attempting a coup, through the massive vote fraud and related attacks on our Republic." Rhodes and several other Oath Keepers were arrested and charged in connection with the attack. At least one member of the Proud Boys pleaded guilty to his involvement in the attack and several other members were arrested and charged. Authorities noted that members of the Proud Boys and Oath Keepers met 24 hours before the attack. Authorities also discovered several social media posts and encrypted messages that demonstrated prior coordination and planning for the January 6 attack, which was an attempt to prevent the confirmation of President BidenÂ’s victory and keep former President Trump in office. Additionally, several assailants displayed confederate flags and displayed Oath Keepers, Proud Boys, Three Percenters, and QAnon conspiracy theory insignias during the attack.
